The Jacobian Conjecture (JC) raised by O.H. Keller in 1939 in [8] states that a polynomial map F:ğŠnâ†’ğŠn:ğ¹â†’superscriptğŠğ‘›superscriptğŠğ‘›F:{\bf{K}}^{n}\rightarrow{\bf{K}}^{n} is invertible if the Jacobian determinant detJâ€‹Fğ½ğ¹\det JF is a nonzero constant. This conjecture has been attacked by many people from various research fields, but it is still open, even for nâ‰¥2ğ‘›2n\geq 2. Only the case n=1ğ‘›1n=1 is obvious. For more information about the wonderful 70-year history, see [1], [5], and the references therein.

In 1980, S.S.S.Wang ([10]) showed that the JC holds for all polynomial maps of degree 2 in all dimensions (up to an affine transformation). The most powerful result is the reduction to degree 3, due to H.Bass, E.Connell and D.Wright ([1]) in 1982 and A.Yagzhev ([12]) in 1980, which asserts that the JC is true if the JC holds for all polynomial maps X+Hğ‘‹ğ»X+H, where Hğ»H is homogeneous of degree 3. Thus, many authors study these maps and led to pose the following problem.
